{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16346"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16346"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.72,0.1,0.06,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9037"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9037"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3879"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the gynaecological clinic with a two-year history of progressively worsening heavy menstrual bleeding and severe dysmenorrhoea. She reports changing pads every hour during the heaviest days of her period and passing large clots. She has no intermenstrual or post-coital bleeding. She has two children born by vaginal deliveries and no significant medical history. Her GP placed a Mirena IUD however this has not improved her symptoms or bleeding. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well but tired. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a tender, boggy uterus palpable at the umbilicus. Investigations show haemoglobin 95 g/L (115-160), mean cell volume 75 fL (80-100), ferritin 8 \u03bcg/L (20-200). Transvaginal ultrasound shows a globular uterus with heterogeneous myometrial echotexture and poor definition of the endometrial-myometrial junction. She undergoes a total laparoscopic hysterectomy. Histological examination of the uterus reveals endometrial glands and stroma within the myometrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leiomyoma","Adenomyosis","Endometriosis","Endometrial hyperplasia","Endometrial carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical presentation and histological findings are classic for adenomyosis. The condition is characterised by the presence of endometrial tissue (glands and stroma) within the myometrium, typically affecting women in their 40s and 50s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenomyosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with heavy menstrual bleeding, dysmenorrhoea, and a tender, enlarged uterus. Ultrasound findings of a globular uterus with heterogeneous myometrial echotexture and poor endometrial-myometrial junction definition are characteristic. Definitive diagnosis requires histological examination showing endometrial tissue within the myometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeiomyomas\u003C/strong\u003E (fibroids) are discrete masses within the myometrium that would appear as well-defined masses on ultrasound. While they can cause heavy menstrual bleeding, they would not show endometrial tissue within the myometrium on histology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E involves proliferation of the endometrium itself and would not explain the presence of endometrial tissue within the myometrium. It typically presents with irregular or heavy bleeding but would show thickened endometrium on ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with postmenopausal or irregular bleeding rather than cyclic heavy menstrual bleeding. Histology would show malignant endometrial cells rather than normal endometrial tissue within the myometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E involves endometrial tissue outside the uterus entirely, not within the myometrium. While it can cause severe dysmenorrhoea, it would not typically cause such significant heavy menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adenomyosis is characterised by the presence of endometrial tissue within the myometrium.","Heavy menstrual bleeding with dysmenorrhoea in women over 40 years should raise suspicion for adenomyosis.","Definitive diagnosis of adenomyosis requires histological examination of the uterus."],"references":["Gunther R, Walker C. Adenomyosis [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 24]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539868/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T18:39:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T18:40:16+10:30"},"relationships"